{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180917190147|860009730","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Duncan_D._Hunter","to":"Duncan D. Hunter"}],"pages":{"17910806":{"pageid":17910806,"ns":0,"title":"Duncan D. Hunter","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-19T14:56:38Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{for|his father and predecessor|Duncan Hunter}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image        = Duncan D. Hunter official photo.jpg\n|office       = Member of the<br>[[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[California's 50th congressional district|California's 50th district]]\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Brian Bilbray]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = Member of the<br>[[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[California's 52nd congressional district|California's 52nd district]]\n|term_start1  = January 3, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 3, 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Duncan Hunter]]\n|successor1   = [[Scott Peters (politician)|Scott Peters]] \n|birth_name   = Duncan Duane Hunter\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1976|12|7}}\n|birth_place  = [[San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Margaret Jankowski|1998}}\n|father       = [[Duncan Hunter]]\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[San Diego State University]] (BS in Information Systems)\n|website      = {{url|hunter.house.gov|House website}}\n|residence    = [[Alpine, California]]\n|allegiance   = {{flagu|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Marine Corps}}\n|serviceyears = 2001\u20132005 (active)<br>2005\u20132017 (reserve)\n|rank         = [[File:US Marine O4 shoulderboard.svg|25px]] [[Major (United States)|Major]]\n|unit         = [[1st Battalion, 11th Marines]]\n|battles      = [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br>[[Iraq War]]\n}}\n'''Duncan Duane Hunter''' (born December 7, 1976) is an American politician serving as a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[California]] since 2009. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he represents parts of [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]]; {{ushr|CA|52}} from 2009 to 2013 and subsequently {{ushr|CA|50}}.\n\nThis district covers much of inland [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]], including the cities of [[El Cajon, California|El Cajon]], [[Escondido, California|Escondido]], [[San Marcos, California|San Marcos]], [[Santee, California|Santee]] and [[Temecula, California|Temecula]]. Prior to his election, Hunter served in the [[United States Marines Corps|U.S. Marines]] from 2001 through 2005. Hunter was elected to the congressional seat succeeding his father, Republican Congressman [[Duncan Hunter|Duncan Lee Hunter]]. \n\nIn 2017, the Department of Justice began a criminal investigation of Hunter for alleged campaign finance violations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hunter under criminal investigation for alleged campaign finance violations |author=John Bresnahan |date=March 23, 2017 |newspaper=[[Politico]] |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/duncan-hunter-campaign-finance-investigation-236422}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=GOP Rep. Hunter under criminal campaign finance investigation |author=Megan R. Wilson |date=March 23, 2017 |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/325457-gop-rep-hunter-under-criminal-campaign-finance-investigation}}</ref> In August 2018, Hunter and his wife were indicted on charges including conspiracy, [[wire fraud]], and violating campaign finance laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/21/politics/duncan-hunter-campaign-charges/index.html|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter and his wife indicted in use of campaign funds for personal expenses|last=Jarrett|first=Laura|date=August 21, 2018|publisher=CNN|access-date=August 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Reagan Contact Sheet C51491 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|The Hunter family with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1989]]\nHunter was born in [[San Diego]], [[California]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/104308/duncan-hunter |title=Representative Duncan D. Hunter's biography|year=2013|publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref> the son of Helynn Louise (n\u00e9e Layh) and [[Duncan Hunter|Duncan Lee Hunter]].<ref>{{cite news|title=District attorney happy to do her bit on jury duty|author=Diane Bell|url=http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/bell/20040219-9999_1m19bell.html|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=February 19, 2013|accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/hunterdd.htm |title=duncan d hunter |publisher=Ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-21}}</ref> He graduated from [[Granite Hills High School (El Cajon, California)|Granite Hills High School]] in [[El Cajon, California]], and [[San Diego State University]], where he earned a degree in [[information systems]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.sdsu.edu/alumni/spotlight/Hunter|title=Alumni Spotlight: U.S. Rep. Duncan D. Hunter|work=San Diego State University, Fowler College of Business|accessdate=10 September 2018}}</ref> During college, Hunter started a [[web design]] company. After graduation. he worked in San Diego as an information technology business analyst.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kitto|first=Kris|url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/24151-the-normal-life-of-duncan-d-hunter|title=The 'normal' life of Duncan D. Hunter|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=March 4, 2009|accessdate=October 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nThe day after the [[September 11 attacks]], Hunter quit his job and joined the [[United States Marine Corps]].<ref name=\"Bade\">{{cite news |last=Bade |first=Rachael |last2=Bresnahan |first2=John |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/08/duncan-hunter-campaign-funds-fbi-397621 |title=From Fallujah to FBI investigation: The undoing of Duncan Hunter |work=[[Politico]] |date=2018-08-22 |accessdate=2018-08-22 }}</ref> He attended [[Officer Candidates School (U.S. Marine Corps)|Officer Candidates School]] at [[Marine Corps Base Quantico]]; when he graduated in March 2002, he was commissioned as a [[second lieutenant]]. He subsequently served as a [[field artillery]] officer in the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and completed a second tour in [[Fallujah, Iraq]], in 2004, serving in Battery A, [[1st Battalion, 11th Marines]]. During his second tour, he participated in [[Operation Vigilant Resolve]],  where he fought in battles in Fallujah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hunter.house.gov/biography|title=Biography: Congressman Duncan D. Hunter|work=U.S. House of Representatives|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2005, Hunter was honorably discharged from active duty; he remained in the [[Marine Forces Reserve|Marine Corps Reserve]] until 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/pentagon-congress/2018/08/21/duncan-hunter-gop-lawmaker-and-marine-vet-indicted-on-corruption-charges/|title=Duncan Hunter, GOP lawmaker and Marine vet, indicted on corruption charges|last=Shane|first=Leo III|date=August 21, 2018|work=Military Times|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> After his 2005 discharge he started a [[residential development]] company. In 2007, he was recalled to active duty and deployed to [[Afghanistan]] in support of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]; this was his third tour of duty during the [[War on Terrorism]]. He was promoted to captain in 2006 and to major in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hunter.house.gov/biography|title=Biography|publisher=Congressman Duncan Hunter |accessdate=April 28, 2013|quote=Still a marine reservist, he was promoted to captain in 2006, and to major in 2012.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=CONGRESS: Temecula part of Hunter's district |author=Jeff Horseman|url=http://www.pe.com/local-news/politics/jeff-horseman-headlines/20130222-congress-temecula-part-of-hunters-district.ece|newspaper=[[The Press-Enterprise]]|date=February 22, 2013|accessdate=April 28, 2013|quote=Temecula is home to a number of marines stationed at Camp Pendleton, and Hunter is a major in the Marine Corps Reserve who served two tours in Iraq and another in Afghanistan.}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an August 2018 report in ''[[Politico]]'', Hunter still experiences the trauma of his wartime deployments as an artillery officer in Afghanistan and Iraq.<ref name=\"Bade\" />\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2008====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2008#District 52}}\nOn March 20, 2007, Hunter's father, [[Duncan Lee Hunter]], announced that as part of his presidential bid he would not seek re-election to the House of Representatives in 2008,<ref name=\"ap032107\">{{cite news|url=http://legacy.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/politics/20070321-1248-ca-hunter-2008.html|title=Duncan Hunter's son looking to replace him in House|date=March 21, 2007|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |accessdate=February 4, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018232702/http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/politics/20070321-1248-ca-hunter-2008.html|archivedate=2015-10-18}}</ref> retiring from Congress after fourteen terms.<ref name=UnionTribune_20080604>{{cite news |first=Michele |last=Clock |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/20080604-9999-1n4cong.html |title=Hunter takes GOP primary |work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |date=June 4, 2008 |accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter Hunter announced his candidacy for his father's seat, he was recalled by the [[United States Marine Corps]] to serve in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]]. On June 3, 2008, Hunter won the Republican primary with 72% of the vote in a four-candidate field and became the Republican nominee to replace his father, representing the 52nd District.<ref name=\"ap032107\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008-statewide-direct-primary/complete-sov.pdf|title=Statement of Vote|author=[[Debra Bowen]]|date=June 3, 2008|publisher=California Secretary of State |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Hunter defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[Mike Lumpkin]], 56%\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008-general/sov_complete.pdf |title=Statement of Vote |author=[[Debra Bowen]] |date=November 4, 2008 |publisher=California Secretary of State |accessdate=January 24, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506165548/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008-general/sov_complete.pdf |archivedate=May 6, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name=StarsandStripes_20081106>{{cite news |url=http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=58659|title=Six recent combat veterans win congressional races|first=Leo, III|last=Shane|work=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]|date=November 6, 2008}}</ref> Hunter became the first combat veteran of either Iraq or Afghanistan to serve in the U.S. Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/rep_duncan_d_hunter.html|title=Rep. Duncan D. Hunter|year=2012 |newspaper=[[Politico]] |accessdate=March 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Chief Petty Officer Lesley Maceyak|title=News: US Rep. Duncan Hunter Jr. tours Navy Lab, awards GWOT medals|url=http://www.dvidshub.net/news/94605/us-rep-duncan-hunter-jr-tours-navy-lab-awards-gwot-medals#.VKw8Y9LF98E|newspaper=Space and Naval Warfare Systems Command|location=San Diego|date=September 12, 2012|accessdate=January 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=B. J. Coleman|title=Congressman Duncan D. Hunter squares off against challenger James Kimber in debate sponsored by Veterans Campaign|url=http://www.thealpinesun.com/article/congressman-duncan-d-hunter-squares-against-challenger-james-kimber-debate-sponsored-veteran|newspaper=The Alpine Sun|date=October 4, 2014|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2010#District 52}}\nHunter won re-election to a second term with 63% of the vote, defeating Democrat Ray Lutz and Libertarian Michael Benoit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-primary/pdf/2012-complete-sov.pdf|title=Statement of Vote|author=[[Debra Bowen]]|date=January 6, 2011|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=January 24, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018061943/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-primary/pdf/2012-complete-sov.pdf|archive-date=October 18, 2012|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012#District 50}}\nAfter redistricting, Hunter's district was renumbered as the [[California's 50th congressional district|50th District]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Walker, Mark |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/local/sdcounty/article_b78544d7-463f-5501-8ec6-a7de447b33f8.html |title=REGION: Saldana is against Bilbray as redistricting completed|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=2011-08-16|accessdate=2013-12-06}}{{dead link|date=May 2017}}</ref> It was pushed well to the east to cover most of inland [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]].\n\nIn the five-candidate open primary in 2012, Hunter ranked first with 67% of the vote; Democratic nominee David Secor ranked second with 17% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-primary/pdf/2012-complete-sov.pdf|title=Statement of Vote|author=[[Debra Bowen]]|date=June 5, 2012|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=January 24, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018061943/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-primary/pdf/2012-complete-sov.pdf|archive-date=October 18, 2012|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In the general election, Hunter defeated Secor 68%\u201332%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-general/sov-complete.pdf |title=Statement of Vote |author=[[Debra Bowen]] |date=November 6, 2012 |publisher=California Secretary of State |accessdate=January 24, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224021529/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-general/sov-complete.pdf |archivedate=December 24, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2014#District 50}}\nIn the primary election, Hunter finished first with 62,371 votes (70%) to Democrat James H. Kimber's 21,552 (24%). In the general election, Hunter defeated Kimber by 111,997 votes (71%) to 45,302 (29%).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/22/duncan-hunter-midterm-election-results_n_5865098.html|title=California Congressman Duncan Hunter Re-Elected|date=November 5, 2014|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2016#District 50}}\nIn the primary election, Hunter took 56.5% of the vote against four opponents. In the general election, he defeated Democrat Patrick Malloy, 63.9% to 36.1%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/california-house-district-50-hunter-malloy|title=California U.S. House 50th District Results: Duncan D. Hunter Wins|date=December 16, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2018#District 50}}\nHunter filed to run [[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2018#District 50|for a sixth term]], which would begin January 2019. His campaign was predicted to be more challenging than usual due to an ongoing FBI investigation of campaign funds.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bellatoni|first1=Christina|last2=Westfall|first2=Julie|last3=Wisk|first3=Allison|title=California could flip the House, and these 13 races will make the difference|url=http://www.latimes.com/projects/la-pol-ca-california-congressional-race-rankings/|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wire|first1=Sarah D.|last2=Cook|first2=Morgan|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter sets up legal fund amid criminal investigation|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-fund-20180424-story.html |work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |date=April 24, 2018 |accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref> Several [[Democratic Party of California|Democrats]] challenged Hunter, including [[Ammar Campa-Najjar]] and Josh Butner. Hunter was also challenged by the Republican Mayor of [[El Cajon, California|El Cajon]], Bill Wells.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/politics/sd-me-wells-congress-20180219-story.html|title=El Cajon mayor announces he will challenge Rep. Duncan Hunter for Congress|author1=Lauryn Schroeder |author2=Karen Pearlman|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref> In the [[Nonpartisan blanket primary|jungle primary]], Hunter received the most votes at 47.4%, followed by Campa-Najjar at 17.6%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vote.sos.ca.gov/returns/us-rep/district/50|title=2018 California Primary Election Results |publisher=California Secretary of State |access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref><ref>Mike Levine & Benjamin Siegel, [Republican Congressman Duncan Hunter, an early endorser of Donald Trump, indicted], ABC News (August 22, 2018).</ref> The two will face off in the November general election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/politics/sd-me-elex-congress-20180605-story.html|title=Diane Harkey, Mike Levin, lead in 49th District; Rep. Duncan Hunter with big lead in 50th|last=Stewart|first=Joshua|date=June 6, 2018|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news |last1=Mai-Duc |first1=Christine |title=Ammar Campa-Najjar advances to face embattled Rep. Duncan Hunter in November |url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-california-primary-june-live-ammar-campa-najjar-advances-to-face-1528302263-htmlstory.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 6, 2018 |accessdate=June 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nFollowing in the footsteps of his father, Hunter's voting record has been decidedly [[Conservatism|conservative]]. He has a lifetime rating of 93 from the [[American Conservative Union]]. He is also a member of the [[Republican Study Committee]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> a caucus of conservative House Republicans of which his father was a longtime member.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nIn a 2009 interview with [[KPBS-FM|KPBS]], Hunter expressed support for \"overriding\" the designation of the [[delta smelt]] as an [[endangered species]], saying that overriding it would reduce unemployment in California.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rep. Duncan D. Hunter Discusses First Year in Office, Economy, Health Care|author=Hank Cook|author2=Doug Myrland|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2009/jun/11/rep-duncan-d-hunter-discusses-first-year-office-ec|newspaper=KPBS|date=June 11, 2009|accessdate=March 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHunter opposed the [[Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010]], saying that it would \"take away\" the doctor-patient relationship and the right for people to choose \"what type of operations they have\", and that it would allow a \"government bureaucrat\" to make health care decisions for people. In the KPBS interview, Hunter said, \"Things that you have problems with now would be exacerbated if you had government-run healthcare.\"<ref name=kpbs61109>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2009/jun/11/rep-duncan-d-hunter-discusses-first-year-office-ec|title=Rep. Duncan D. Hunter Discusses First Year in Office, Economy, Health Care|last=Crook|first=Hank|author2=Doug Myrland|date=June 11, 2009|publisher=[[KPBS Public Media|KPBS]]|accessdate=February 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt an April 2010 [[Tea Party movement]] rally in [[Ramona, California]], Hunter advocated for the deportation of United States citizens who are the children of illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/04/lawmaker-from-calif-wants-to-deport-children-of-illegal-immigrants/1|work=[[USA Today]]|title=Calif. congressman wants to deport children of illegal immigrants|date=April 28, 2010}}</ref> At the rally, Hunter said, \"It's a complex issue and ... you could look and say, 'You're a mean guy. That's a mean thing to do. That's not a humanitarian thing to do' ... We simply cannot afford what we're doing right now. We just can't afford it. California's going under.\" He confirmed the comments to San Diego County's ''[[North County Times]]'', telling the newspaper that he supported House Resolution 1868, a measure that called for the elimination of [[birthright citizenship in the United States]]. He expressed support for the controversial [[Arizona immigration law (2010)|2010 Arizona immigration law]], calling it a national security issue and \"a fantastic starting point\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fox5sandiego.com/news/kswb-hunter-calls-for-deportation,0,1239838.story|title=Congressman's call to deport children of illegals sparks firestorm|last=Ponting|first=Bob|date=April 29, 2010|publisher=[[KSWB-TV]] |accessdate=February 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Hunter voted against an amendment offered by [[Justin Amash]] to rein in warrantless domestic surveillance conducted by the NSA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Amash amendment: the full roll call|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/25/amash-amendment-full-roll-call|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=July 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 Hunter was the only representative from San Diego County to vote against the bill ending the nation's 16-day [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|partial government shutdown]], explaining that he voted against it because it did not reduce spending or the national debt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2013/oct/17/hunter-congress-vote-budget/|title=Duncan Hunter explains 'no' vote on shutdown bill; Alpine Republican was county congressional delegation's only vote against deal|last=Walker|first=Mark|date=October 17, 2013|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Hunter puffed on an [[electronic cigarette]] during a committee hearing, to dramatize his opposition to a proposed federal ban on such \"vaping\" on airplanes; however, his colleagues on the House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee approved the ban.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ktla.com/2016/02/11/republican-congressman-uses-vaporizer-during-hearing-about-use-of-device-on-airplanes|title=California Rep. Duncan Hunter Vapes During Congressional Hearing on Use of E-Cigarettes on Planes|date=February 11, 2016|publisher=[[KTLA]] |accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt a town-hall-style meeting in March 2017, Hunter was confronted by protesters. Before the crowd, Hunter asserted that the American intelligence community was filled with \"seditious Obama folks\" who \"hate Donald Trump as much as you [those at the meeting] do\" and are trying to undermine the Trump administration. He also described the American government as \"Orwellian\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Figueroa|first1=Teri|last2=Stewart|first2=Joshua|title=Reps. Issa and Hunter confronted by protesters at separate town halls|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-ca-pol-issa-hunter-townhalls-20170311-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 12, 2017 |accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHunter voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite news|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html |website=The New York Times |date=December 19, 2017 |accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> Hunter said that the plan is \"good for most states\" but \"not as good\" for California.<ref name=\"Elias122217\">{{cite news |last1=Elias|first1=Thomas D.|title=Thomas D. Elias: State's GOP Congress members put selves at risk|url=http://napavalleyregister.com/news/opinion/columnists/thomas_d_elias/thomas-d-elias-state-s-gop-congress-members-put-selves/article_6118a258-a731-55fd-906a-eccb901bdf53.html|newspaper=Napa Valley Register|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Military affairs====\nHunter opposed the repeal of the [[don't ask, don't tell]] policy, which barred gays and lesbians from serving openly in the United States military. In 2011, Hunter advocated for delaying the implementation of the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]], which was signed into law by U.S. President [[Barack Obama]]. In 2011, Hunter introduced legislation to require that all \"four military service chiefs certify that the repeal of Don't Ask Don't Tell won't negatively affect their combat units\".<ref>{{cite news |authors=Megan Burke & Gloria Penner|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2011/jan/21/sd-congressman-challenges-dont-ask-dont-tell-repea|title=SD Congressman Challenges Don't Ask Don\u2019t Tell Repeal|date=January 21, 2011|publisher=[[KPBS Public Media|KPBS]]}}</ref>\n\nColumnist Dan Murtaugh of the ''[[Press-Register]]'' has suggested that Hunter's 2011 call to rebid the [[littoral combat ship]] program is an attempt to get federal funds for a shipyard in his district.<ref>Murtaugh, Dan. [http://blog.al.com/press-register-business/2011/07/congressman_asks_for_lcs_progr.html \"Congressman asks for LCS program review, possible rebidding\"], ''Press-Register'', July 7, 2011.</ref> Hunter turned again to the LCS program in 2012, with a call to reduce LCS builds in favor of amphibious ships, because he had read a report that the Marines had leased a ferry with similar characteristics to the LCS and the [[Joint High Speed Vessel]] (JHSV).<ref>Robbins, Gary. [http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/sep/14/hunter-says-navy-may-need-fewer-littoral-combat-sh/ \"Hunter: Navy may need fewer littoral combat ships\"], ''[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]'', September 14, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn a 2011 op-ed in ''[[Politico]]'', Hunter opposed a complete withdrawal of American forces from Afghanistan, because of \"unreliable Afghan leadership\"; he accused the Obama administration of \"echoing a misshapen worldview that puts American interests last\".<ref>{{cite news|title=How to handle Afghanistan|author=Duncan D. Hunter|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0611/56116.html|newspaper=Politico|date=June 3, 2011|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref> In October 2012, Hunter returned from a visit to Afghanistan, as part of a [[congressional delegation]], with a more upbeat assessment, stating \"Frankly I was very skeptical last year when I went last, and have been, on whether [the Afghans] can do this, but they are.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Hunter reports progress in Afghan war effort|author=Gretel C. Kovach|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2012/oct/20/hunter-reports-progress-in-afghan-war-effort|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306111501/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2012/oct/20/hunter-reports-progress-in-afghan-war-effort|dead-url=yes|archive-date=March 6, 2016|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=October 20, 2013|accessdate=January 26, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Hunter said the [[United States Navy]] was overworked and spread thin, and said that a \"306-ship target might represent the absolute minimum capacity the navy needs\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Hunter Opposes Plan for Smaller Navy Fleet|author=Jeanette Steele|url=http://m.utsandiego.com/news/2013/feb/06/tp-hunter-opposes-plan-for-smaller-navy-fleet|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=February 6, 2013|accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Hunter said that if a U.S. war with [[Iran]] becomes inevitable, which he \"sure as hell\" hoped wouldn't happen, the American response should be a \"massive aerial bombing campaign\" including \"[[Tactical nuclear weapon|tactical nuclear devices]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://freebeacon.com/hunter-if-you-hit-iran-do-it-with-tactical-nuclear-devices|title=Hunter: If You Hit Iran, Do It With Tactical Nuclear Devices|publisher=Washington Free Beacon|accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> He also said that the culture of Middle Easterners made them unreliable negotiating partners.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20131204/DEFREG02/312040017/Rep-Hunter-US-Should-Use-Tactical-Nukes-Iran-Strikes-Become-Necessary|title=Rep. Hunter: US Should Use Tactical Nukes on Iran if Strikes Become Necessary|last1=Bennett|first1=John T.|work=[[Defense News]] |accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHunter has strongly criticized the Army's use of its internally developed [[DCGS-A]] system for tracking battlefield intelligence. He says that an alternative technology developed by [[Palantir Technologies]] is more effective at identifying [[improvised explosive devices|IEDs]] and is preferred by Army personnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2014/04/22/congressman-battles-army-officials-over-why-soldiers-dont-have-bomb-predicting-software|title='Matter of Life and Limb': The Congressman Who's Going to Battle With the Army Over a Software Program|last=Carter|first=Sara|date=April 22, 2014|publisher=TheBlaze|accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> He stated that if Lt. Gen. [[Mary A. Legere]] were nominated to head the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]], he would oppose her due to her support of the DCGS-A system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/205041-hunter-opposes-possible-nominee-to-lead-pentagon-spy-agency|title=Rep. Hunter opposes possible nominee to lead Pentagon spy agency|last=Matishak|first=Martin|date=May 2, 2014|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Hunter called for the United States to train and arm Syrian rebels and said that President Obama would be breaking the law if he bombed Syria without a Congressional mandate, and that bombing should be considered an impeachable offense.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/-734934--.html|title=SYRIA: Duncan Hunter visits border, urges arming opposition group|last1=Horseman|first1=Jeff|date=August 27, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press-Enterprise]] |location=Riverside |accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/3/hunter-obama-inviting-impeachment-strikes-syria|title=Hunter: Obama inviting impeachment if he strikes Syria without Congress|last1=Dinan|first1=Stephen|date=September 3, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Washington Times]] |accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> In September 2014, however, Hunter voted against a proposal to train and arm [[Free Syrian Army|Syrian rebels]] fighting against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] extremists, saying that the proposal failed to go far enough.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2014/09/17/duncan-hunter-votes-obamas-syria-request|title=Rep. Hunter Is Lone S.D. Vote Against Obama's Syria Request|last1=Jennewein|first1=Chris|date=September 17, 2014|publisher=Times of San Diego}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Hunter introduced legislation into the [[111th Congress]] to allow [[Tobacco in the United States|tobacco]] products to be shipped to service members serving in Iraq and Afghanistan;<ref>{{cite news|title=Hunter seeks loophole to let troops get smokes|author=Rick Maze|url=http://marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/08/military_mail_tobacco_080210w|newspaper=Marine Corps Times|date=August 2, 2010|accessdate=March 10, 2013}}</ref> the legislation died after being referred to committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/111th-congress/house-bill/6037|title=H.R.6037 \u2013 To amend title 18, United States Code, to provide for an exception to the prohibition against mailing tobacco products for products mailed to members of the Armed Forces serving in a combat zone.|publisher=congress.gov |accessdate=March 10, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, Hunter moved to block a plan by the military to [[Smoking in the United States military|ban sales of tobacco products on bases and ships]], indicating that he believes service members should be able to make their own choices regarding use of tobacco.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.navytimes.com/article/20140507/NEWS05/305070077/Lawmakers-move-block-Navy-plan-restrict-tobacco-sales|title=Lawmakers move to block Navy plan to restrict tobacco sales|last1=Shane III|first1=Leo|date=May 7, 2014|newspaper=Navy Times |accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, Huner was one of 17 veterans of the Iraq War serving in the U.S. House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defenseone.com/politics/2014/06/D1-otoole-iraq-war-veterans-congress-mostly-urge-caution/86704/|title=Iraq War Veterans In Congress Mostly Urge Caution|last=O'Toole|first=Molly|date=June 18, 2014|work=Defense One|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> He has called for the system of awarding the [[Medal of Honor]] to be reevaluated, due to the cases of Sergeant [[Rafael Peralta]] and Captain [[William D. Swenson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Defense too stingy with Medal of Honor, says Duncan Hunter|author=Charles Hoskinson|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65789.html|newspaper=Politico|date=October 12, 2011|accessdate=January 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Congressman: Medal of Honor system broken|author=Stephen Dinan|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/aug/13/congressman-medal-honor-system-broken|newspaper=Washington Times|date=August 13, 2012|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The changing process of awarding military's highest medal: Peralta case an example of modern methods interfering with witness accounts, vets say|author=John Wilkens|url=http://m.utsandiego.com/news/2012/dec/23/changing-process-of-awarding-highest-medal|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=December 23, 2012|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref> Even after Secretary of Defense [[Chuck Hagel]] became the third Secretary to deny the award to Peralta, Hunter maintained his pressure on the Pentagon. In late March 2014, he sent a letter asking the Pentagon to reevaluate Peralta's case, as well as the case of [[Bradley Kasal]], who used his body to shield a fellow Marine from a grenade blast in Iraq in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.militarytimes.com/article/20140325/NEWS/303250074/Lawmaker-Grant-all-Marines-who-cover-grenades-Medal-Honor|title=Lawmaker: Grant all Marines who cover grenades the Medal of Honor|date=March 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Hunter opposed a proposal floated by the Trump administration to cut the [[U.S. Coast Guard]]'s annual budget by $1.3 billion, calling the proposed budget cut \"an insult\" and \"an appalling mistake\".<ref>Duncan Hunter, [http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2017/03/07/rep-duncan-hunter-slashing-coast-guards-budget-is-appalling-mistake-that-puts-our-nation-at-risk.html Slashing the Coast Guard's budget is an appalling mistake that puts our nation at risk], Fox News (March 7, 2017).</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nHunter introduced the [[Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation Act of 2014 (H.R. 4005; 113th Congress)]] into the House on February 6, 2014.<ref name=4005sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4005 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4005|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> The bill would amend laws that govern the activities of the [[United States Coast Guard]] (USCG), the [[United States Maritime Administration|Maritime Administration]] (MARAD) within the [[United States Department of Transportation|Department of Transportation]], and the [[Federal Maritime Commission]] (FMC).<ref name=4005cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4005 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45168|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"TransportPR\">{{cite web|title=Committee Leaders Introduce Coast Guard & Maritime Transportation Bill|url=https://transportation.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=369179|publisher=House Transportation Committee |author=Jim Billimoria |author2=Justin Harclerode |date=February 6, 2014 |accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> One provision increased to 75% the proportion of food aid that must be transported on private U.S.-flagged cargo ships. The bill was signed into law on December 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr5769|title=H.R. 5769 (113th): Howard Coble Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation Act of 2014|publisher=GovTrack |accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHunter opposes women in combat and, to make a rhetorical point, in 2016 he introduced an amendment to the defense authorization act to require 18-to-26-year old women to register for the [[Selective Service System]] (as 18-to-26-year old men are required to do). This backfired, however, as the House Armed Services Committee voted 32-30 to adopt the amendment.<ref>Karoun Demirjian, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2016/04/28/women-could-be-headed-for-the-draft-after-house-committee-vote/ Are women headed for the draft? Support for the idea grows in Congress], ''Washington Post'' (April 28, 2016).</ref><ref>Tara Golshan, [https://www.vox.com/2016/4/28/11526292/women-draft-open-combat-military-amendment How a too-clever attempt to oppose women in combat turned into a bill opening the draft to women], ''Vox'' (April 28, 2016).</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nIn late August 22, 2018, after being indicted on 60 federal charges, Paul Ryan forced Hunter to resign from all of the following Congressional committees and subcommittees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/23/duncan-hunter-indicted-house-committees-794859|title=Hunter steps down from House committee assignments|last=Bade|first=Rachel|date=August 22, 2018|work=POLITICO|access-date=August 24, 2018|language=en}}</ref>.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n* Committee on Armed Services (resigned) \n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities|Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities]] (resigned)\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]] (resigned)\n* Committee on Education and the Workforce (resigned)\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]] (resigned)\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]] (resigned)\n* Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation|Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation]] (resigned) (ex-Chairman)\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]] (resigned)\n** Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment (resigned)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=March 23, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=June 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n=== Abortion ===\nHunter is [[Anti-abortion movements|anti-abortion]] and believes life begins at [[Fertilisation|conception]]. He has consistently voted against all forms of abortion, as well as cloning and [[embryonic stem cell]] research. He voted in favor of criminalizing harm to a fetus during another crime, against funding family planning overseas, and in favor of giving fetuses [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|14th Amendment]] protections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/112th-congress/house-bill/374/text|title=H.R.374 - Life at Conception Act|last=|first=|date=|publisher=Congress.gov |access-date=May 27, 2017}}</ref> Hunter voted to ban the \"morning after\" pill in the case of rape or incest, and would like to ban [[Intrauterine device|IUDs]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2011/11/mississippi-personhood-zygote-federal-law|title=Congressional GOP Pushes Zygote Personhood Bills|work=Mother Jones|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\nHe has been rated 0% by the abortion-rights group [[NARAL Pro-Choice America|NARAL]] and 100% by the anti-abortion [[National Right to Life Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Duncan_Hunter.htm|title=Duncan Hunter on the Issues |publisher=OnTheIssues |access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate change ===\nHunter does not believe [[climate change]] is caused by humans, and believes it may actually be positive. He has said about climate change, \"Nobody really knows the cause ... It could be caused by [[carbon dioxide]] or [[methane]]. Maybe we should kill the cows to stop the methane, or stop breathing to stop the CO<sub>2</sub> ... Thousands of people die every year of cold, so if we had global warming it would save lives ... We ought to look out for people. The earth can take care of itself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2013/may/20/obama-urges-san-diegans-call-out-rep-duncan-hunter/|title=Obama Urges San Diegans To 'Call Out' Rep. Duncan Hunter On Climate Change Denial|last=Wagner|first=David|publisher=KPBS Public Media|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\nHunter does not believe the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] should be allowed to regulate [[Greenhouse gas emissions by the United States|greenhouse gas emissions]] and has consistently voted against any governmental limits to CO<sub>2</sub> pollution. He would like to open up [[oil drilling]] in the United States in order to bring down [[gas prices]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Duncan_Hunter_Jr__Energy_+_Oil.htm|title=Duncan Hunter Jr. on Energy & Oil|publisher=OnTheIssues |access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\nHunter was an early supporter of Trump, endorsing him in February 2016 in the earliest days of the Republican primary.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/2016-gop-primary-live-updates-and-results/2016/02/duncan-hunter-endorses-donald-trump-219725|title=Duncan Hunter endorses Donald Trump|last=Gass|first=Nick|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=November 21, 2016|publisher=Politico blogs}}</ref> He was the second member of Congress to support him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/trump-duncan-hunter-chris-collins-indictments_us_5b7caf60e4b07295150dd6cb|title=The First 2 Congressmen To Endorse Trump Have Been Indicted|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Terkel|first2=Amanda|date=August 21, 2018|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> According to anonymous sources, during an address to [[Riverside County, California|Riverside County]] Young Republicans in late August 2017, Hunter said of President Donald Trump, \"He's just like he is on TV ... He's an asshole, but he\u2019s our asshole.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/politics/sd-me-hunter-trump-20170827-story.html |title=Rep. Duncan Hunter gives President Trump a profane compliment |author=Stewart, Joshua |date=August 28, 2017 |newspaper=San Diego Union-Tribune |accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Gender issues ===\nHe voted against the [[Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009]], an act which made it easier to file lawsuits regarding [[wage discrimination]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/111/house/1/votes/9/|title=Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009 {{!}} U.S. Congress Votes Database |publisher=The Washington Post |access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Hunter voted in favor of renewing the [[Violence Against Women Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/113-2013/h55 |title=S. 47 (113th): Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2013 |publisher=GovTrack.us |date=2013-02-28 |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref> He supported the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] (DOMA), which restricted federal recognition of marriage to [[Heterosexuality|opposite-sex couples]] only, and cut off [[federal benefits]] to [[same-sex couples]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hunter.house.gov/issue/family-values|title=Family Values {{!}} Congressman Duncan Hunter|publisher=hunter.house.gov|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref> He voted to delay the repeal of [[Don't ask, don't tell|Don't Ask, Don't Tell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/rep-duncan-hunter-homosexual-lobby-will-takeover-the-military-86c949fdd031|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter: 'Homosexual Lobby' Will 'Takeover' The Military|date=2011-10-14|publisher=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\nOn the question of [[Transgender people and military service|transgender military personnel]], Hunter said that as a [[Marine Corps]] veteran, he could not imagine sharing a shower with \"somebody who was a girl and didn't have the surgery to become a man but kept the girl stuff\".<ref name=\"Hill-170628\">{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/339994-republicans-slam-pentagon-transgender-policy-leave-it-in-place-for-now |title=Republicans leave transgender policy in place for now |author=Kheel, Rebecca |date=June 28, 2017 |newspaper=The Hill |accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nHunter favors repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and voted in support of a budget resolution to repeal it in January 2017.<ref name=\"On The Issues\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Duncan_Hunter_Jr_.htm|title=Duncan Hunter Jr. on the Issues |publisher=OnTheIssues |access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\nHe has expressed support for all drafts of the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|AHCA]], which would partially repeal and replace Obamacare, and voted for the AHCA on May 4, 2017. About the AHCA he said, \"this is going to save America.\"<ref name=\"LA Times 2017-05-25\">{{Cite news |date=May 25, 2017 |url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-ca-essential-politics-updates-rep-duncan-hunter-weighs-in-on-alleged-1495725515-htmlstory.html|title=California politics updates: State lawmakers weigh in on hundreds of bills by week's end, apology sought for cutting off Waters' microphone|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Mediaite 2017-03-23\">{{cite web |author=Justin Baragona |date=March 23, 2017 |url=http://www.mediaite.com/online/this-is-going-to-save-america-gop-congressman-on-american-health-care-act/|title='This is Going to Save America': GOP Congressman on American Health Care Act |publisher=Mediaite |access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nHe voted against renewing the [[Violence Against Women Act]] in part because it would allow battered [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigrants]] to claim [[Visa (document)|temporary visas]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/15/us/politics/violence-against-women-act-divides-senate.html|title=Violence Against Women Act Divides Senate|last=Weisman|first=Jonathan|date=2012-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Press relations ===\nAfter a reporter from ''[[The Guardian]]'' was assaulted by a Republican from Montana,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/judge-releases-congressman-gianforte-s-mugshot/article_af6ccc66-e32d-5b76-9c46-fec7f41e9069.html|title=Judge releases Congressman Gianforte's mugshot|last=Bermes|first=Whitney|work=Bozeman Daily Chronicle|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> Hunter's response was published in several newspapers. In response to questions about the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|AHCA's]] effect on those with pre-existing conditions, Gianforte put his hands around the reporter's neck and \"bodyslammed\" him to the ground, injuring his elbow and breaking his glasses. Hunter commented: \"It's not appropriate behavior. Unless the reporter deserved it.\"<ref name=\"LA Times 2017-05-25\" />\n\n=== Smoking ===\n\nHunter is a former smoker and uses an [[electronic cigarette|e-cigarette]], which he credits with helping him quit [[cigarette]]s. He opposes the banning of e-cigarettes on airplanes. Hunter puffed on his e-cigarette during a congressional hearing about vaping.<ref name=\"Cadelago21116\">{{cite web|last1=Cadelago|first1=Christopher|title=California Rep. Duncan Hunter blows smoke at congressional hearing|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article59814136.html|newspaper=The Sacramento Bee |date=February 11, 2016 |accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign finance investigation and indictment==\nIn April 2016, Hunter came under scrutiny from the [[Federal Elections Commission]] regarding his use of campaign funds for personal expenses from 2015 to 2016, after [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] filed an ethics complaint.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sdut-hunter-video-games-2016apr05-htmlstory.html|title=FEC questions Duncan Hunter's video game charges|last1=Cook|first1=Morgan|date=April 5, 2016|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico 2017-08-09\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/08/09/duncan-hunter-fbi-search-241456|title=FBI searched campaign office tied to Duncan Hunter|work=Politico |access-date=2017-12-28}}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times 2017-03-23\">{{Cite news |date=March 23, 2017 |url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-hunter-campaign-spending-20170323-story.html |title=FBI is investigating San Diego-area Rep. Duncan Hunter for possible campaign finance violations |first1=Sarah D. |last1=Wire |first2=Morgan |last2=Cook |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2017-12-28}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, the [[Office of Congressional Ethics]] made a recommendation to the Ethics Committee for a full investigation into Hunter. Hunter and his wife, Margaret, who was being paid $3,000 monthly from campaign funds in her role as campaign manager, shared a campaign fund credit card which had charges which were questioned.<ref name=\"CookCutShort\">{{Cite new |first=Morgan |last=Cook |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sdut-hunter-repay-2016apr07-htmlstory.html |title=Hunter to cut short Israel trip, repay campaign funds |newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> The expenses included $1,302 in charges for video games, $600 to pay for a family rabbit to travel by plane, clothing from [[Abercrombie & Fitch]],<ref name=\"LA Times 2017-03-23\" /> a donation to their son's school, payments to an [[Oral and maxillofacial surgery|oral and maxillofacial surgeon]], travel costs including 32 payments for airfare, hotel stays in Arizona and Italy,<ref name=\"LA Times 2017-03-23\" /> groceries, a nail salon visit, tuition, non-specified items at a surf shop,<ref name=\"San Diego Union 2017-07-18\">{{Cite news|date=July 18, 2017 |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-spending-20170718-story.html|title=Hunter's campaign ramps up spending on attorneys amid probe|last=Cook|first=Morgan|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=2017-12-28}}</ref> and outdoor equipment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-spending-20161116-story.html|title=Duncan Hunter's campaign expenses detailed: Nail salon, dentist, more|last=Cook|first=Morgan|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=2017-12-28}}</ref>  \n\nIn February 2017, Hunter's campaign offices were raided by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] as part of a criminal investigation. Agents seized computers, other electronics, and financial records; they also seized a hard drive from Election CFO, an Alexandria, Virginia-based company that handled campaign finances on Hunter's behalf.<ref name=\"Politico 2017-08-09\" /> The raid was not reported in the media until August 2017, after court documents intended to be filed under seal were accidentally released to the public.<ref name=\"Politico 2017-08-09\" />\n\nOn March 23, 2017, the [[House Ethics Committee]] revealed that Hunter was under a [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] criminal investigation for alleged campaign finance violations, and that it was deferring its own investigation as a result.<ref name=\"CrimInv\">[http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/duncan-hunter-campaign-finance-investigation-236422 \"Rep. Hunter under criminal investigation for alleged campaign finance violations], ''Politico'', March 23, 2017.</ref> The Office of Congressional Ethics report stated: \"Rep. Hunter may have [[Conversion (law)|converted]] tens of thousands of dollars of campaign funds from his congressional campaign committee to personal use to pay for family travel, flights, utilities, health care, school uniforms, and tuition, jewelry, groceries, and other goods, services, and expenses.\"<ref name=\"LA Times 2017-03-23\" /><ref>Tom LoBianco, [http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/23/politics/duncan-hunter-justice-investigation/index.html?sr=twpol032617duncan-hunter-justice-investigation1036PMVODtopLink&linkId=35868039 DOJ investigating Rep. Duncan Hunter, early Trump backer], CNN (March 23, 2017).</ref> Hunter said that he repaid the money to the campaign, and denied wrongdoing. He also announced that his wife would no longer receive a $3000 per month salary for consulting the campaign.<ref name=\"LA Times 2017-03-23\" /> His lawyers Gregory Vega and Elliot Berkewas said that any improper use of campaign funds was \"inadvertent and unintentional\".<ref name=\"Politico 2017-08-09\" /><ref name=\"CrimInv\" /> In March 2017, in a statement issued through his lawyers, Hunter said that he had repaid his campaign approximately $60,000 in 2016.<ref name=\"CrimInv\" /> In April 2017, Hunter returned from international travel in order address  issues around his campaign funds, promising to correct any inappropriate or mistaken charges.<ref name=\"CookCutShort\" />\n\nOn August 21, 2018, a federal grand jury of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of California]] indicted Hunter and his wife on 60 counts of wire fraud, falsifying records, campaign finance violations, and conspiracy.<ref name = indicted>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-indict-20180821-story.html|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter and wife indicted on fraud and campaign finance charges|last1=Cook|first1=Morgan|last2=McDonald|first2=Jeff|date=August 21, 2018|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> The San Diego U.S. Attorney's Office accused the couple of conspiring to misuse $250,000 in campaign funds for personal expenses, as well as filing false campaign finance reports.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/21/politics/duncan-hunter-campaign-charges/index.html|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter and his wife indicted in use of campaign funds for personal expenses |author=Laura Jarrett |author2=Maeve Reston |publisher=CNN|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> Personal expenses charged to the campaign included vacations in Italy and Hawaii, theater tickets,<ref>{{cite web|last=Blood |first=Michael R. |url=https://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/SD-Congressman-Duncan-Hunter-Indicted--491405712.html |title=SD Congressman Duncan Hunter, Wife Indicted for Misuse of Campaign Funds |publisher=NBC 7 San Diego |date=2011-01-05 |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref> and purchases in the gaming platform [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|author=By Zergnet |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/congressman-indicted-for-misuse-of-campaign-funds-including-dollar1500-for-steam-games/ |title=Congressman indicted for misuse of campaign funds, including $1,500 for Steam games |publisher=PC Gamer |date=2014-09-11 |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref> The indictment says that when Hunter wanted to buy some shorts for himself, his wife suggested that he falsely report the purchase as \"golf balls for [[Wounded Warrior Project|wounded warriors]]\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Sarah D. Wire, Christine Mai-Duc |url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-duncan-hunter-indict-20180821-story.html# |title=San Diego County Rep. Duncan Hunter and his wife are indicted on campaign finance violations |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date= |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |date=August 21, 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/21/politics/read-duncan-hunter-indictment/index.html |title=Rep. Duncan Hunter indicted: |publisher=CNN |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref> On another occasion he tried unsuccessfully to arrange a tour of a Navy base as a cover for a family vacation trip to Italy.<ref>{{cite web|author=By $${element.Contributor} |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/duncan-hunter-navy-curse |title=Duncan Hunter in Indictment: 'Tell the Navy to Go F*** Themselves' |newspaper=Roll Call |date= |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref> When the Navy couldn't arrange something on the date Hunter wanted, Hunter told his chief of staff to \"tell the Navy to go fuck themselves.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Emma Ockerman|url=https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/mb4nnv/heres-all-the-insane-stuff-vaping-congressman-duncan-hunter-charged-to-his-campaign-credit-cards |title=Here\u2019s all the insane stuff \u201cvaping congressman\u201d Duncan Hunter charged to his campaign credit cards|newspaper=Vice|date=August 22, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2018}}</ref> The indictment also alleges that Hunter spent campaign money on \"personal relationships\" with five women in Washington DC, listed as Individuals 14, 15, 16, 17, and 18 in the indictment.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-liaisons-20180830-story.html |title=Hunter indictment sheds light on 'personal relationships' for congressman |first1=Jeff |last1=McDonald |first2=Morgan |last2=Cook |work=San Diego Union Tribune |access-date=2018-09-08 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[Speaker of the House]] [[Paul Ryan]] called the charges \"deeply serious\" and stripped Hunter of his committee assignments.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-22/california-congressman-quickly-loses-clout-after-indictment|title=Ryan Strips Indicted GOP Lawmaker of Committee Assignments|last1=Pettersson|first1=Edvard|last2=House|first2=Billy|date=August 22, 2018|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> At first Hunter said he would not resign from his committees, but eventually did so after the Republican Steering Committee indicated they would vote to remove him from them.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/duncan-hunter-i-am-not-going-anywhere-after-being-targeted-by-politically-motivated-doj|title=Duncan Hunter: 'I am not going anywhere' after being targeted by 'politically motivated' DOJ|last=Weaver|first=Al|date=August 22, 2018|work=Washington Examiner|accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/403048-duncan-hunter-to-be-forced-from-committee-assignments|title=Duncan Hunter refuses to relinquish committee posts, may be forcibly removed|last=Keller|first=Megan|date=August 22, 2018|work=The Hill|accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref> The ''[[San Diego Union Tribune]]'', Hunter's hometown paper, published an editorial calling for him to resign from Congress.<ref name=\"resign\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/editorials/sd-duncan-hunter-indictment-20180821-story.html|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter, do the honorable thing. Resign.|last=The San Diego Union Tribune Editorial board|date=August 21, 2018|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> Hunter's father, the [[Duncan Hunter|former congressman]], attacked the indictment as a \"late hit\" and claimed it was politically motivated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/Politicians-React-to-Duncan-Hunter-Indictment-491427632.html|title=Politicians, Hunter's Father React to Hunter Indictment|last=Stimson|first=Brie|date=August 21, 2018|work=NBC San Diego|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Hunter himself insisted that he never used campaign funds for personal expenses and that the indictment was a \"witch hunt\" carried out by \"partisan Democrat prosecutors\" and the \"deep state\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-main-20180822-story.html|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter says Democrats, &apos;deep state&apos; behind indictment, says he&apos;s not resigning - The San Diego Union-Tribune|last1=Dyer|first1=Andrew|last2=Davis|first2=Kristina|date=August 23, 2018|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> The ''Union-Tribune'' pointed out that the local U.S. Attorney's office is led by Adam L. Braverman, a Trump administration appointee.<ref name = \"resign\"/> \n\nOn August 23, 2018, both Hunter and his wife pleaded not guilty to all charges. The two entered and left the courtroom separately and were represented by separate counsel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/23/politics/duncan-hunter-not-guilty-plea/index.html|title=Duncan Hunter and his wife plead not guilty to charges they misused campaign funds|last=Reston|first=Maeve|date=August 23, 2018|publisher=CNN|accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref> Hunter has suggested his wife is to blame for any irregularities, saying that she handled all their personal and campaign finances and adding, \"I didn't do it. I didn't spend any money illegally.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/23/politics/duncan-hunter-wife-margaret-campaign-finances/index.html|title=Indicted Rep. Duncan Hunter: My wife handled my finances|last=Sullivan|first=Kate|date=August 24, 2018|work=CNN|accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHunter married Margaret Jankowski in 1998. They have three children.<ref name=timeline /> In 2016, Hunter sold his home in [[Alpine, California]] and used part of the proceeds to repay the political campaign for some of the money that was spent on personal expenses. He and his family moved in with his father [[Duncan Hunter|Duncan L. Hunter]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=861 |title=Duncan L. Hunter |website=Our Campaigns |access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref name = indicted/><ref name=timeline>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/local-history/sd-me-hunter-timeline-20180821-story.html|title= Hunter timeline: Son of a congressman serves in military, gets elected |work=San Diego Union-Tribune|date=August 21, 2018|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"long-ago murderer\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-loan-20161214-story.html|title=Rep. Duncan Hunter repays campaign with loan brokered by long-ago murderer|last=Cook|first=Morgan|date=December 14, 2016|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"campaign expenses\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-hunter-spending-20161116-story.html|last=Cook|first=Morgan|title= Duncan Hunter's campaign expenses detailed: Nail salon, dentist, more |work=San Diego Union-Tribune|date=November 16, 2016|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://hunter.house.gov Congressman Duncan D. Hunter] official U.S. House site\n* [https://hunterforcongress.com Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Duncan_Hunter_%5BR-50%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|duncandhunter}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Duncan Hunter]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from California|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[California's 52nd congressional district]]|years=2009\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Scott Peters (politician)|Scott Peters]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Bilbray]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from California|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[California's 50th congressional district]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Himes]]<br>D-[[Connecticut]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=167th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lynn Jenkins]]<br>R-[[Kansas]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Duncan D.}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Baptists from the United States]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from California]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:People from El Cajon, California]]\n[[Category:Politicians from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:San Diego State University alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps officers]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps reservists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Alpine, California]]"}]}}}}